aa(lp50
VSo with PISA, we try to change this
p51
aVby measuring the knowledge and skills
p52
aVof people directly.
p53
aVAnd we took a very special angle to this.
p54
aVWe were less interested in whether students can simply
p55
aVreproduce what they have learned in school,
p56
aVbut we wanted to test whether they can extrapolate
p57
aVfrom what they know
p58
aVand apply their knowledge in novel situations.
p59
aVNow, some people have criticized us for this.
p60
aVThey say, you know, such a way of measuring outcomes
p61
aVis terribly unfair to people, because we test students
p62
aVwith problems they haven't seen before.
p63
aVBut if you take that logic, you know,
p64
aVyou should consider life unfair, because
p65
aVthe test of truth in life is not whether we can remember
p66
aVwhat we learned in school,
p67
aVbut whether we are prepared for change,
p68
aVwhether we are prepared for jobs that haven't been created,
p69
aVto use technologies that haven't been invented,
p70
aVto solve problems we just can't anticipate today.
p71
aa(lp72
VAnd once hotly contested,
p73
aVour way of measuring outcomes has actually quickly become the standard.
p74
aVIn our latest assessment in 2009,
p75
aVwe measured 74 school systems
p76
aVthat together cover 87 percent of the economy.
p77
aVThis chart shows you the performance of countries.
p78
aVIn red, sort of below OECD average.
p79
aVYellow is so-so, and in green are the countries doing really well.
p80
aVYou can see Shanghai, Korea, Singapore in Asia;
p81
aVFinland in Europe;
p82
aVCanada in North America doing really well.
p83
aVYou can also see that there is a gap of almost
p84
aVthree and a half school years between
p85
aV15-year-olds in Shanghai and 15-year-olds in Chile,
p86
aVand the gap grows to seven school years
p87
aVwhen you include the countries with really poor performance.
p88
aVThere's a world of difference in the way in which
p89
aVyoung people are prepared for today's economy.
