aa(lp91
VBut I want to introduce a second important dimension
p92
aVinto this picture.
p93
aVEducators like to talk about equity.
p94
aVWith PISA, we wanted to measure how they actually deliver equity,
p95
aVin terms of ensuring that people
p96
aVfrom different social backgrounds have equal chances.
p97
aVAnd we see that in some countries, the impact
p98
aVof social background on learning outcomes
p99
aVis very, very strong.
p100
aVOpportunities are unequally distributed.
p101
aVA lot of potential of young children is wasted.
p102
aVWe see in other countries that it matters much less
p103
aVinto which social context you're born.
p104
aVWe all want to be there, in the upper right quadrant,
p105
aVwhere performance is strong and learning opportunities are equally distributed.
p106
aVNobody, and no country, can afford to be there,
p107
aVwhere performance is poor
p108
aVand there are large social disparities.
p109
aVAnd then we can debate, you know, is it better
p110
aVto be there, where performance is strong
p111
aVat the price of large disparities?
p112
aVOr do we want to focus on equity and accept mediocrity?
p113
aVBut actually, if you look at how countries come out on this picture,
p114
aVyou see there are a lot of countries that actually
p115
aVare combining excellence with equity.
p116
aVIn fact, one of the most important lessons from this comparison
p117
aVis that you don't have to compromise equity
p118
aVto achieve excellence.
p119
aVThese countries have moved on from providing excellence
p120
aVfor just some to providing excellence for all,
p121
aVa very important lesson.
p122
aVAnd that also challenges the paradigms of many school systems
p123
aVthat believe they are mainly there to sort people.
p124
aVAnd ever since those results came out, policymakers,
p125
aVeducators, researchers from around the world
p126
aVhave tried to figure out
p127
aVwhat's behind the success of those systems.
p128
aa(lp129
VBut let's step back for a moment
p130
aVand focus on the countries that actually started PISA,
p131
aVand I'm giving them a colored bubble now.
p132
aVAnd I'm making the size of the bubble
p133
aVproportional
p134
aVto the amount of money that countries spent on students.
p135
aVIf money would tell you everything
p136
aVabout the quality of learning outcomes,
p137
aVyou would find all the large bubbles at the top, no?
p138
aVBut that's not what you see.
p139
aVSpending per student only explains about,
p140
aVwell, less than 20 percent
p141
aVof the performance variation among countries,
p142
aVand Luxembourg, for example, the most expensive system,
p143
aVdoesn't do particularly well.
p144
aVWhat you see is that two countries with similar spending
p145
aVachieve very different results.
p146
aVYou also see \u2014 and I think that's one of the most encouraging findings \u2014
p147
aVthat we no longer live in a world that is neatly divided
p148
aVbetween rich and well-educated countries,
p149
aVand poor and badly-educated ones,
p150
aVa very, very important lesson.
