aa(lp152
VLet's look at this in greater detail.
p153
aVThe red dot shows you
p154
aVspending per student relative to a country's wealth.
p155
aVOne way you can spend money is by paying teachers well,
p156
aVand you can see Korea investing a lot
p157
aVin attracting the best people into the teaching profession.
p158
aVAnd Korea also invests into long school days,
p159
aVwhich drives up costs further.
p160
aVLast but not least, Koreans want their teachers
p161
aVnot only to teach but also to develop.
p162
aVThey invest in professional development and collaboration
p163
aVand many other things.
p164
aVAll that costs money.
p165
aVHow can Korea afford all of this?
p166
aVThe answer is, students in Korea learn in large classes.
p167
aVThis is the blue bar which is driving costs down.
p168
aVYou go to the next country on the list, Luxembourg,
p169
aVand you can see the red dot is exactly where it is for Korea,
p170
aVso Luxembourg spends the same per student as Korea does.
p171
aVBut, you know, parents and teachers and policymakers
p172
aVin Luxembourg all like small classes.
p173
aVYou know, it's very pleasant to walk into a small class.
p174
aVSo they have invested all their money into there,
p175
aVand the blue bar, class size, is driving costs up.
p176
aVBut even Luxembourg can spend its money only once,
p177
aVand the price for this is that
p178
aVteachers are not paid particularly well.
p179
aVStudents don't have long hours of learning.
p180
aVAnd basically, teachers have little time to do anything else than teaching.
p181
aVSo you can see two countries spent their money very differently,
p182
aVand actually how they spent their money
p183
aVmatters a lot more than how much they invest in education.
