aa(lp236
VOr take Korea, at the other end of the spectrum.
p237
aVIn the year 2000, Korea did already very well,
p238
aVbut the Koreans were concerned that only a small share
p239
aVof their students achieved the really high levels of excellence.
p240
aVThey took up the challenge,
p241
aVand Korea was able to double the proportion of students
p242
aVachieving excellence in one decade in the field of reading.
p243
aVWell, if you only focus on your brightest students,
p244
aVyou know what happens is disparities grow,
