aa(lp270
VAnd all that raises, of course, the question: What can we learn
p271
aVfrom those countries in the green quadrant
p272
aVwho have achieved high levels of equity,
p273
aVhigh levels of performance, and raised outcomes?
p274
aVAnd, of course, the question is, can what works in one context
p275
aVprovide a model elsewhere?
p276
aVOf course, you can't copy and paste education systems wholesale,
p277
aVbut these comparisons have identified a range of factors
p278
aVthat high-performing systems share.
p279
aVEverybody agrees that education is important.
p280
aVEverybody says that.
p281
aVBut the test of truth is, how do you weigh that priority
p282
aVagainst other priorities?
p283
aVHow do countries pay their teachers
p284
aVrelative to other highly skilled workers?
p285
aVWould you want your child to become a teacher
p286
aVrather than a lawyer?
p287
aVHow do the media talk about schools and teachers?
p288
aVThose are the critical questions, and what we have learned
p289
aVfrom PISA is that, in high-performing education systems,
p290
aVthe leaders have convinced their citizens to make choices
p291
aVthat value education, their future,
p292
aVmore than consumption today.
p293
aVAnd you know what's interesting? You won't believe it,
p294
aVbut there are countries in which the most attractive place
p295
aVto be is not the shopping center but the school.
p296
aVThose things really exist.
p297
aa(lp298
VBut placing a high value on education
p299
aVis just part of the picture.
p300
aVThe other part is the belief that all children
p301
aVare capable of success.
p302
aVYou have some countries where students
p303
aVare segregated early in their ages.
p304
aVYou know, students are divided up,
p305
aVreflecting the belief that only some children
p306
aVcan achieve world-class standards.
p307
aVBut usually that is linked to very strong social disparities.
p308
aVIf you go to Japan in Asia, or Finland in Europe,
p309
aVparents and teachers in those countries
p310
aVexpect every student to succeed,
p311
aVand you can see that actually mirrored in student behavior.
p312
aVWhen we asked students what counts
p313
aVfor success in mathematics,
p314
aVstudents in North America would typically tell us,
p315
aVyou know, it's all about talent.
p316
aVIf I'm not born as a genius in math, I'd better study something else.
p317
aVNine out of 10 Japanese students say
p318
aVthat it depends on my own investment, on my own effort,
p319
aVand that tells you a lot about the system that is around them.
p320
aa(lp321
VIn the past, different students were taught in similar ways.
p322
aVHigh performers on PISA embrace diversity
p323
aVwith differentiated pedagogical practices.
p324
aVThey realize that
p325
aVordinary students have extraordinary talents,
p326
aVand they personalize learning opportunities.
p327
aa(lp328
VHigh-performing systems also share
p329
aVclear and ambitious standards across the entire spectrum.
p330
aVEvery student knows what matters.
p331
aVEvery student knows what's required to be successful.
p332
aa(lp333
VAnd nowhere does the quality of an education system
p334
aVexceed the quality of its teachers.
p335
aVHigh-performing systems are very careful
p336
aVin how they recruit and select their teachers
p337
aVand how they train them.
p338
aVThey watch how they improve the performances of teachers
p339
aVin difficulties who are struggling,
p340
aVand how they structure teacher pay.
p341
aVThey provide an environment also in which teachers work together
p342
aVto frame good practice.
p343
aVAnd they provide intelligent pathways for teachers to grow
p344
aVin their careers.
p345
aVIn bureaucratic school systems,
p346
aVteachers are often left alone in classrooms
p347
aVwith a lot of prescription on what they should be teaching.
p348
aVHigh-performing systems are very clear what good performance is.
p349
aVThey set very ambitious standards, but then they enable
p350
aVtheir teachers to figure out,
p351
aVwhat do I need to teach to my students today?
p352
aVThe past was about delivered wisdom in education.
p353
aVNow the challenge is to enable user-generated wisdom.
p354
aVHigh performers have moved on from professional
p355
aVor from administrative forms of accountability and control \u2014
p356
aVsort of, how do you check whether people do what they're supposed to do in education \u2014
p357
aVto professional forms of work organization.
p358
aVThey enable their teachers to make innovations in pedagogy.
p359
aVThey provide them with the kind of development they need
p360
aVto develop stronger pedagogical practices.
p361
aVThe goal of the past was standardization and compliance.
p362
aVHigh-performing systems have made teachers
p363
aVand school principals inventive.
p364
aVIn the past, the policy focus was on outcomes,
p365
aVon provision.
p366
aVThe high-performing systems have helped teachers
p367
aVand school principals to look outwards to the next teacher,
p368
aVthe next school around their lives.
p369
aa(lp370
VAnd the most impressive outcomes of world-class systems
p371
aVis that they achieve high performance across the entire system.
p372
aVYou've seen Finland doing so well on PISA,
p373
aVbut what makes Finland so impressive
p374
aVis that only five percent of the performance variation
p375
aVamongst students lies between schools.
p376
aVEvery school succeeds.
p377
aVThis is where success is systemic.
p378
aVAnd how do they do that?
p379
aVThey invest resources where they can make the most difference.
p380
aVThey attract the strongest principals into the toughest schools,
p381
aVand the most talented teachers
p382
aVinto the most challenging classroom.
p383
aa(lp384
VLast but not least, those countries align policies
p385
aVacross all areas of public policy.
p386
aVThey make them coherent over sustained periods of time,
p387
aVand they ensure that what they do is consistently implemented.
p388
aa(lp389
VNow, knowing what successful systems are doing
p390
aVdoesn't yet tell us how to improve.
p391
aVThat's also clear, and that's where some of the limits
p392
aVof international comparisons of PISA are.
p393
aVThat's where other forms of research need to kick in,
p394
aVand that's also why PISA doesn't venture into
p395
aVtelling countries what they should be doing.
p396
aVBut its strength lies in telling them
p397
aVwhat everybody else has been doing.
p398
aVAnd the example of PISA shows that data
p399
aVcan be more powerful than administrative control of financial subsidy
p400
aVthrough which we usually run education systems.
